    {\displaystyle L_{\mathbf {x} }={\begin{bmatrix}0&0&0\\0&0&-1\\0&1&0\end{bmatrix}},\quad L_{\mathbf {y} }={\begin{bmatrix}0&0&1\\0&0&0\\-1&0&0\end{bmatrix}},\quad L_{\mathbf {z} }={\begin{bmatrix}0&-1&0\\1&0&0\\0&0&0\end{bmatrix}}.}

Exponential map
Connecting the Lie algebra to the Lie group is the exponential map, which is defined using the standard matrix exponential  series for eA For any skew-symmetric matrix A, exp(A) is always a rotation matrix.An important practical example is the 3 × 3 case. In rotation group SO(3), it is shown that one can identify every A ∈ so(3) with an Euler  vector ω = θu, where u = (x, y, z) is a unit magnitude vector.
By the properties of the identification 
  
    
      
        
          s
          u
        
        (
        2
        )
        ≅
        
          
            R
          
          
            3
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \mathbf {su} (2)\cong \mathbb {R} ^{3}}
  , u is in the null space of A. Thus, u is left invariant by exp(A) and is hence a rotation axis.
According to Rodrigues' rotation formula on matrix form, one obtains,

  
    
      
        
          
            
              
                exp
                ⁡
                (
                A
                )
              
              
                
                =
                exp
                ⁡
                
                  
                    (
                  
                
                θ
                (
                
                  u
                
                ⋅
                
                  L
                
                )
                
                  
                    )
                  
                
              
            
            
              
              
                
                =
                exp
                ⁡
                
                  (
                  
                    
                      [
                      
                        
                          
                            0
                          
                          
                            −
                            z
                            θ
                          
                          
                            y
                            θ
                          
                        
                        
                          
                            z
                            θ
                          
                          
                            0
                          
                          
